Configured Splunk to Receive Logs & Joined Windows 11 to Active Directory

Active Directory Configuration
On Windows Server 2022 (DC01) :

Installed Active Directory Certificate Services (AD CS)
Configured Root CA (Certificate Authority) for the lab.local domain
Kept all default settings during CA configuration

On Windows 11 :

Attempted domain join with Windows 11 Home — failed, Home edition does not support domain join
Downloaded Windows 11 Enterprise evaluation ISO from microsoft.com/evalcenter
Reinstalled VM with Windows 11 Enterprise
Joined domain lab.local via Settings → Accounts → Access work or school → Join this device to a local Active Directory domain
Enabled ICMP inbound firewall rule to allow ping from other VMs
Confirmed domain join successful — Windows 11 visible in AD Users and Computers under Computers container


Sysmon Installation
Installed Sysmon on both Windows Server 2022 and Windows 11 to generate detailed Windows event logs.
Steps (repeated on both machines) :

Downloaded Sysmon from learn.microsoft.com/sysinternals/downloads/sysmon
Downloaded SwiftOnSecurity configuration file via PowerShell. Used Claude to generate the exact command
Installed Sysmon with SwiftOnSecurity config via PowerShell
Verified Sysmon running via PowerShell
Verified logs appearing in Event Viewer → Applications and Services Logs → Microsoft → Windows → Sysmon → Operational


Splunk Universal Forwarder Installation
Installed Splunk Universal Forwarder on both Windows Server 2022 and Windows 11 to forward logs to Splunk.
Steps (repeated on both machines) :

Downloaded Universal Forwarder .msi from splunk.com
Installed with Receiving Indexer set to Ubuntu Splunk server (port 9997)
Added forwarding destination, monitor paths and restarted forwarder via PowerShell
Verified logs flowing into Splunk via Search & Reporting


Troubleshooting

Windows 11 Home cannot join domain : reinstalled with Windows 11 Enterprise evaluation ISO
Ping blocked from Windows Server to Windows 11 : enabled ICMP inbound rule on Windows 11 firewall
No data in Splunk after forwarder install : forwarding destination was not configured. Fixed by adding Splunk server manually via PowerShell
Splunk receiving port not configured : added port 9997 via Settings → Forwarding and Receiving → Configure Receiving in Splunk web interface
Windows 11 host not appearing in Splunk : forwarder had no monitor paths configured. Added Event Log paths manually via PowerShell


Verification
Confirmed both machines sending logs to Splunk. Confirmed Sysmon events visible in Splunk Search & Reporting.
